09:35.620 --> 09:37.953
Libby, we have both suffered,

09:37.955 --> 09:41.841
but we are lucky
that we found each other.

09:41.876 --> 09:43.959
Libby:
We didn't find each other.

09:44.011 --> 09:46.262
I was a crutch,
as you were for me.

09:46.297 --> 09:48.430
Now you have
that rarest of things.

09:48.466 --> 09:50.466
You have a new life
ahead of you.

09:50.551 --> 09:51.567
Paul: And you?

09:51.602 --> 09:54.436
Libby:
I... I have a lot of practice

09:54.472 --> 09:56.188
taking care of myself.

09:56.224 --> 09:57.473
I will be fine.

09:57.525 --> 09:58.691
Paul: [ Sighs ]

09:58.726 --> 10:00.726
Libby: Paul, I am making this
easy for you.

10:00.778 --> 10:02.611
Paul: I don't need it
to be easy.

10:02.647 --> 10:04.029
Libby:
I want you to be happy.

10:04.065 --> 10:05.681
Paul: Libby,
I am happy with you.

10:08.736 --> 10:10.736
Libby: I want you
to be with someone else.

10:14.242 --> 10:17.209
[ Indistinct conversations ]

10:22.416 --> 10:24.300
Ronald: Dr. Masters.

10:26.170 --> 10:27.503
William: Are you in the mood

10:27.505 --> 10:29.505
for being escorted from
the premises again, Ronald?

10:29.557 --> 10:31.590
Ronald:
Well, if that's what it takes.

10:31.642 --> 10:34.310
The Lord has made certain
knowledge available to me,

10:34.345 --> 10:37.012
and I am compelled to share
that knowledge with you.

10:37.014 --> 10:39.682
William: You must be petrified
of me to keep this up.

10:39.734 --> 10:42.484
Ronald: No, I am just frightened
of what you are doing.

10:42.520 --> 10:44.403
William: Do you actually know
what it is I'm doing, Ronald?

10:44.438 --> 10:45.955
I'm saving people.

10:45.990 --> 10:48.257
Have you saved anyone lately?

10:48.292 --> 10:50.910
Ronald:
Yes. By spreading God's love.

10:50.945 --> 10:52.194
William: [ Scoffs ]

10:52.246 --> 10:55.414
Yet everything you say
is filled with hate and fear

10:55.449 --> 10:57.366
while I am actually
helping people

10:57.368 --> 10:59.585
give and receive love,
actual love.

10:59.620 --> 11:01.921
So why don't you come back
and see me

11:01.956 --> 11:04.039
when you're ready to be saved?

11:04.041 --> 11:06.091
Ronald:
<i>I</i> am compelled by the Lord

11:06.127 --> 11:09.211
to remind you of the damnation
that awaits you, Dr. Mas--

11:10.765 --> 11:14.717
William: You will feel
the pain of damnation firsthand

11:14.769 --> 11:19.471
if you ever
come into this building again.

11:19.523 --> 11:21.223
[ Elevator dings ]

11:21.275 --> 11:22.658
Look at me, Ronald!

11:22.693 --> 11:27.062
Because I have been sent by God
as a warning.

11:29.317 --> 11:31.951
Nora: It's okay to tell me
about it if you want.

11:31.986 --> 11:33.569
I promise I won't be shocked.

11:34.655 --> 11:39.625
Lester: Well, she was a widow,
or so I thought.

11:39.660 --> 11:41.076
We'd planned
to run away together,

11:41.078 --> 11:43.212
but she stood me up.

11:43.247 --> 11:46.615
Turns out her husband
wasn't so dead after all.

11:46.651 --> 11:49.985
Opened a café after that,
trying to forget her.

11:50.021 --> 11:51.820
Virginia:
He's, uh, doing Bogart?

11:51.856 --> 11:54.139
Nora: What a difficult time
for you, Rick.

11:54.175 --> 11:55.341
Lester: It was.

11:55.426 --> 11:57.026
Yet as time goes by--

11:57.061 --> 11:58.093
Nora: You know, Rick,

11:58.129 --> 11:59.928
I get the feeling
that you like movies.

11:59.964 --> 12:02.364
Lester: - I love movies.
Nora: - Then maybe after dinner,

12:02.400 --> 12:03.999
we can see what's playing
at the Hi Pointe.

12:04.035 --> 12:05.200
William:
That was deftly handled.

12:05.236 --> 12:08.237
Lester: That's--
that's a great idea.

12:08.272 --> 12:10.239
[ Chuckles ]
Thank you.

12:10.274 --> 12:12.024
And thank you
for coming tonight.

12:12.076 --> 12:13.275
I don't really date much

12:13.277 --> 12:15.077
since I can't reach
the end zone,

12:15.112 --> 12:16.545
so why bother taking the snap?

12:16.614 --> 12:18.781
Nora: Because dating
isn't supposed to be

12:18.783 --> 12:19.882
a game or a contest.

12:19.917 --> 12:22.167
The goal should be to have fun,

12:22.203 --> 12:25.220
and I really am
having fun... with you.

12:27.291 --> 12:28.791
Lester: Here's looking at you--

12:28.793 --> 12:30.959
William: Okay, we can leave it
there, Lester. Thank you.

12:31.012 --> 12:33.512
Nora, uh,
you made him comfortable.

12:33.547 --> 12:36.015
You sensed both
his vulnerabilities

12:36.050 --> 12:38.634
and areas of personal interest.

12:38.669 --> 12:39.702
Very well done.

12:39.737 --> 12:41.437
Nora:
I've been taught by the best.

12:41.472 --> 12:46.241
William: [ Chuckles ]
Uh... Wendy, you're next.

12:46.277 --> 12:49.862
And Lester, this time,
a little less drama.

12:49.897 --> 12:51.447
Lester:
I just thought it made sense

12:51.482 --> 12:53.282
that Rick would develop
secondary impotence

12:53.317 --> 12:54.416
after being jilted by Ilsa.

12:54.452 --> 12:55.901
William: Well, let's just
leave the politics

12:55.953 --> 12:57.419
of the Second World War
out of it, shall we?

12:57.455 --> 12:59.238
Lester: Okay.

12:59.290 --> 13:01.490
Wendy: I'm Wendy.
So nice to meet you.

13:01.542 --> 13:02.825
Lester: And you.

13:02.827 --> 13:04.560
I'm... Frederick.

13:04.628 --> 13:06.328
Transferred from Cape Canaveral.

13:06.330 --> 13:08.497
I'm a fighter pilot
in the Air Force.

13:08.499 --> 13:09.898
William: Um...
[ Clears throat ]

13:11.802 --> 13:15.804
Lester: You're from St. Louis
originally?

13:15.840 --> 13:18.006
I'm sorry. Did I--
did I say something wrong?

13:18.059 --> 13:20.259
- I didn't mean to--
Wendy: - No. It's just...

13:22.680 --> 13:25.114
I have a brother
who's a pilot in Vietnam.

13:25.149 --> 13:28.567
It's a constant
source of worry for me,

13:28.602 --> 13:31.787
but especially my mother,
who is really not doing well.

13:37.278 --> 13:38.861
Virginia:
It's a perfect example

13:38.913 --> 13:40.913
of my objections
to the surrogacy program.

13:40.948 --> 13:43.449
The surrogates themselves
are unknowns and unpredictable.

13:43.501 --> 13:45.367
William:
It was a minor error, Virginia.

13:45.369 --> 13:46.418
It's why we train them.

13:46.454 --> 13:47.803
Virginia: And married couples,

13:47.838 --> 13:50.639
who we should be focusing on,
don't need training.

13:50.674 --> 13:51.673
They already know each other.

13:51.709 --> 13:53.125
William:
That's a generous assumption,

13:53.177 --> 13:55.210
given some of the couples we've
seen come through the door.

13:55.212 --> 13:57.012
Virginia: You asked me to watch
with an open mind,

13:57.047 --> 13:58.347
and I watched, and--

13:58.382 --> 14:00.099
William: I don't agree
that your concerns are valid.

14:00.134 --> 14:02.351
Look, each phase of our research

14:02.386 --> 14:04.686
- has involved trial and error.
Virginia: - Bill...

14:04.722 --> 14:06.688
William:
And-- and this is no different.

14:06.724 --> 14:08.724
And when we know
that there are single men

14:08.726 --> 14:10.893
out there suffering
and in need of our help--

14:10.945 --> 14:13.896
Virginia: Yes, of course.
The suffering male.

14:18.736 --> 14:19.735
William: Um...

14:23.574 --> 14:29.244
There are, uh, two new surrogate
volunteers to train.

14:29.246 --> 14:30.879
If it makes you feel better,

14:30.915 --> 14:35.501
then... I will happily leave them
in your capable hands.

14:35.553 --> 14:37.469
Virginia:
Train them yourself, Bill.

14:37.505 --> 14:39.338
I'm busy with
our other research.

14:39.390 --> 14:40.839
William: What other research?

14:40.891 --> 14:43.058
Virginia: The research
that I care about.

14:43.093 --> 14:47.329
[ Door slams ]

14:47.364 --> 14:49.331
Virginia: It's called
the placebo effect.

14:49.366 --> 14:51.316
Dan: We give patients
fake scents?

14:51.352 --> 14:53.769
Virginia: No, there's more to it
than that.

14:53.771 --> 14:56.822
For example, what is your
best-selling perfume to date?

14:56.857 --> 14:57.823
Dan: Two coffees, please.

14:57.858 --> 14:59.241
It's a cologne, in fact.

14:59.276 --> 15:00.442
It's called Rake.

15:00.444 --> 15:01.910
Virginia: - Rake?
Dan: - Mm-hmm.

15:01.946 --> 15:03.612
Virginia:
Because men splash it on

15:03.664 --> 15:05.948
- and think of gardening tools?
Dan: - [ Chuckles ]

15:05.950 --> 15:10.085
Virginia: - Sunday chores?
Dan: - More Don Juan.

15:10.120 --> 15:11.203
We think it sells well

15:11.255 --> 15:13.038
because men
like to envision themselves

15:13.090 --> 15:14.056
as ladies' men.

15:14.091 --> 15:15.457
It gives them confidence
with women.

15:15.509 --> 15:16.675
Virginia: Exactly.

15:16.710 --> 15:18.961
The idea changes the behavior,

15:18.963 --> 15:20.462
also known as
the placebo effect.

15:20.514 --> 15:22.464
Dan: I know this is gonna be
hard to believe

15:22.466 --> 15:23.465
coming from a salesman,

15:23.517 --> 15:24.900
but I don't believe
in fakery.

15:24.935 --> 15:26.385
Virginia: We won't be faking.

15:26.437 --> 15:28.804
Dan: Our scent only arouses
1/4 of the women.

15:28.806 --> 15:31.306
I wouldn't sell a shampoo
that only cleans hair

15:31.308 --> 15:33.075
- one out of every four times.
Virginia: - Yes.

15:33.110 --> 15:34.810
But when the placebo works,

15:34.862 --> 15:37.396
it's effect on the body
is very real.

15:37.448 --> 15:39.982
We see it all the time
in the clinic.

15:39.984 --> 15:42.618
Somebody is suffering
from a sexual dysfunction

15:42.653 --> 15:44.653
and they feel like
there's no hope.

15:44.705 --> 15:46.205
But then they hear about us,

15:46.240 --> 15:47.956
and all of a sudden,
there's a way forward,

15:47.992 --> 15:49.791
a path toward a cure.

15:49.827 --> 15:51.627
Dan: So, we continue with
the study, but tell the women

15:51.662 --> 15:53.262
the thing they're smelling
contains pheromones.

15:53.297 --> 15:54.546
Virginia: Because it does.

15:54.582 --> 15:56.498
And that pheromones
are nature's own aphrodisiacs,

15:56.500 --> 15:58.300
- which they are.
Dan: - We tell them that.

15:58.335 --> 16:01.236
And then we see
if our numbers improve.

16:02.506 --> 16:04.873
Well, this research might keep
me here in St. Louis awhile.

16:06.477 --> 16:08.060
You might be a genius.

16:08.095 --> 16:10.095
Virginia: Well, if you insist.

16:10.147 --> 16:12.431
William: Now, I've been thinking
a lot about this,

16:12.483 --> 16:13.849
and, uh, you said it yourself.

16:13.851 --> 16:15.601
Betty: I don't know
what you're talking about.

16:15.653 --> 16:19.521
William: About looking
the other way, you know?

16:19.523 --> 16:21.490
There has been
far too much of that here,

16:21.525 --> 16:26.161
far too much deceit
and subterfuge, you know?

16:26.196 --> 16:28.363
From now on, no more secrets,

16:28.365 --> 16:32.200
because secrets
tear people apart.

16:32.202 --> 16:33.669
Betty: Sure.

16:33.704 --> 16:36.255
William: Everything just
out in the open.

16:36.290 --> 16:38.040
Betty: Okay.

16:38.092 --> 16:39.508
Um...

16:40.711 --> 16:42.844
You need to modernize
your wardrobe.

16:43.964 --> 16:47.049
William:
Oh, I-I mean Virginia, Betty--

16:47.051 --> 16:49.985
about her time with Dan Logan.

16:50.020 --> 16:51.470
It's blinding her, you know,

16:51.522 --> 16:54.623
diverting her from the work
that we need to be focusing on.

16:56.727 --> 17:01.330
So, we need to find out what's
really going on with Logan.

17:01.365 --> 17:02.998
Betty: We... meaning me?

17:03.067 --> 17:05.867
William: It is vital
to the stability

17:05.903 --> 17:08.236
of everything
that we have built here.

17:08.238 --> 17:11.123
Betty: Okay.

17:11.375 --> 17:12.324
Oh.

17:15.996 --> 17:17.311
William: Hmm?

17:18.582 --> 17:20.132
Oh!

17:20.166 --> 17:21.717
Ah, hell.

17:22.386 --> 17:25.337
[ Indistinct conversations ]

17:29.426 --> 17:31.510
Paul: You did good.
Listen. You did a great job.

17:33.847 --> 17:36.431
Libby: Here you go.
Careful. It's full.

17:36.433 --> 17:37.766
[ Door opens ]

17:37.768 --> 17:39.067
Paul: Okay.

17:40.521 --> 17:43.372
William: Paul, I'm--
I'm sorry I'm late.

17:43.407 --> 17:46.108
Paul: It's okay.
I, uh, gave the speeches.

17:46.160 --> 17:48.076
We're just, uh, waiting on you.

17:48.112 --> 17:50.746
Dennis: I got MVP.
Is my trophy in there?

17:50.781 --> 17:52.497
William: I'm sure it is...
somewhere.

17:52.533 --> 17:54.916
Uh, hopefully,
there are trophies

17:54.952 --> 17:57.502
for all the players
that contributed.

17:57.538 --> 17:59.788
Paul: Okay, Hornets,
bring it in, guys.

17:59.840 --> 18:00.839
Come on over.

18:00.874 --> 18:02.374
Finally,
now that the hardware is here,

18:02.426 --> 18:03.875
we're gonna give out
some awards, okay?

18:05.295 --> 18:06.461
And, uh, I'm gonna make you guys

18:06.513 --> 18:08.130
suffer through
some more boring speeches,

18:08.132 --> 18:09.965
and I apologize for that,
so bear with me, okay?

18:10.017 --> 18:15.270
Stephanie:
He is so good with kids.

18:15.305 --> 18:17.973
I think coaching's
been a real solace for Paul

18:17.975 --> 18:20.192
during this time of upheaval.

18:20.227 --> 18:21.910
Libby: I think it has.

18:21.945 --> 18:23.612
Stephanie: We should probably
organize something

18:23.647 --> 18:24.680
with Joy's other girlfriends,

18:24.715 --> 18:27.866
make sure he stays fed,
don't you think?

18:27.901 --> 18:30.736
Or, you know,
I could just... feed him.

18:30.788 --> 18:32.320
Libby: It's been two months.

18:32.322 --> 18:34.489
He's hardly wasting away.
[ Chuckles ]

18:34.541 --> 18:36.992
Stephanie: Libby,
I'm looking for an excuse.

18:36.994 --> 18:39.578
You're gonna think
I'm terrible,

18:39.630 --> 18:43.331
but how long, exactly,
does a widower have to wait

18:43.384 --> 18:46.418
before he can start,
you know... eating?

18:46.470 --> 18:48.670
Libby: I don't know.

18:48.672 --> 18:49.771
A year?

18:49.807 --> 18:52.057
Stephanie: [ Scoffs ]
Says who?

18:52.092 --> 18:55.177
Libby: Says...
Emily Post, I've heard.

18:55.179 --> 18:57.763
Stephanie: Well, Emily post
is also a divorcée,

18:57.815 --> 19:00.732
so she would definitely be
on my side.

19:00.768 --> 19:04.352
And a delicious man like that
shouldn't go to waste.

19:04.354 --> 19:05.520
[ Sighs ]

19:05.572 --> 19:07.355
Don't you want Paul
to be happy?

19:11.528 --> 19:13.445
Libby: Of course I do.

19:13.497 --> 19:15.914
Yeah, he's--
he's lost his wife,

19:15.949 --> 19:18.583
and you are recently divorced,
so...

19:18.619 --> 19:22.204
Stephanie: So...
you don't mind playing Cupid?

19:23.006 --> 19:25.707
Paul: Also, certainly,
a thank you to Coach Masters

19:25.759 --> 19:28.877
for his--
his help on the field.

19:30.347 --> 19:31.630
[ Claps ]

19:31.682 --> 19:35.550
[ Applause ]

19:35.552 --> 19:36.968
♪

19:37.020 --> 19:40.605
[ Indistinct conversations ]

19:40.641 --> 19:42.107
Libby: - Paul...
Paul: - Yeah?

19:42.142 --> 19:44.226
Libby: You remember Stephanie,
Jacob's mom.

19:44.278 --> 19:45.977
Paul: Of course.
Hi. How are you?

19:46.029 --> 19:47.395
Libby:
You may not be aware,

19:47.397 --> 19:49.531
but Stephanie is, uh--
she's recently divorced.

19:49.566 --> 19:51.616
Stephanie: [ Chuckles ]
Oh, well, that got to the point.

19:51.652 --> 19:52.868
[ Chuckles ]
To the--

19:52.903 --> 19:54.536
Oh, you're setting us up.

19:54.571 --> 19:56.488
Stephanie:
It was my idea. I know.

19:56.540 --> 19:58.907
But at some point, I thought,
"Why be coy?"

19:58.909 --> 20:00.292
Libby: She's right.

20:00.327 --> 20:03.712
I mean, you're both single,
you're both smart and nice.

20:03.747 --> 20:06.465
Paul:
Smart and nice. Wow.

20:06.500 --> 20:09.684
Stephanie,
can I offer you a refill?

20:09.720 --> 20:11.586
Stephanie: - Yes. Thank you.
Paul: - You're very welcome.

20:14.057 --> 20:15.056
Here you go.

20:15.092 --> 20:17.225
[ <i> Laughter</i> ]

20:17.261 --> 20:18.693
Helen:
If we ever have a daughter,

20:18.729 --> 20:20.195
we should do her hair
like that.

20:20.230 --> 20:21.963
Betty: - Oh, like Jeannie's?
Helen: - Yes.

20:21.999 --> 20:24.399
Betty: No, no. You got to be
born in a lamp.

20:24.434 --> 20:25.484
Helen: No, it's adorable!

20:25.519 --> 20:26.518
I could do it one day,

20:26.570 --> 20:28.270
and then you could do it
the next day.

20:28.272 --> 20:30.438
[ Knock on door ]

20:30.491 --> 20:33.158
Betty: - But no hat.
Helen: - I love the hat!

20:33.193 --> 20:34.442
Betty: Hel, that hat looks like

20:34.495 --> 20:37.445
it's for a monkey
who should be clanging a symbol.

20:38.582 --> 20:39.781
Austin.

20:39.783 --> 20:42.701
Okay. How does
the other guy look?

20:42.753 --> 20:44.920
Helen: Oh, no. You're not
gonna be one of those exes

20:44.955 --> 20:46.171
that shows up when he's drunk?

20:46.206 --> 20:47.706
Even though we're not exes.

20:47.758 --> 20:49.624
Even though we only did it once.

20:49.626 --> 20:51.343
Austin: They're gone.

20:51.378 --> 20:53.261
Betty: What? Who's gone?

20:53.297 --> 20:55.130
Austin: [ Crying ]
My kids.

20:55.182 --> 20:58.099
I lost custody of my kids.

20:58.135 --> 20:59.968
Betty: Oh.

20:59.970 --> 21:02.554
Okay. Okay. All right.
Get in.

21:02.606 --> 21:04.272
Helen: Austin, I'm so sorry.

21:04.308 --> 21:06.057
Austin: [ Breathing shakily ]

21:06.109 --> 21:07.442
Betty: It's all right.

21:07.477 --> 21:11.029
Austin: The judge said,
and I will quote him directly

21:11.064 --> 21:14.316
because he was such
a complete and utter asshole...

21:14.318 --> 21:17.285
Betty: Sure. You know,
get comfortable.

21:17.321 --> 21:19.871
Austin:
He said that I was unfit.

21:19.907 --> 21:22.958
Now, all my life, people have
told me that I'm <i> very</i> fit.

21:22.993 --> 21:25.760
My Uncle Lionel was
in the fucking Olympics, okay?

21:25.796 --> 21:27.829
Helen: I didn't know that.

21:27.831 --> 21:29.381
Archery?

21:29.416 --> 21:30.799
Austin: Pentathlon.

21:30.834 --> 21:33.752
So, to tell me
that I am unfit now

21:33.804 --> 21:36.254
when my fitness really matters,

21:36.306 --> 21:40.058
when the fitness stakes
couldn't be higher...

21:44.147 --> 21:46.231
Here I am!

21:46.266 --> 21:48.984
With nothing left! Nothing!

21:49.019 --> 21:54.689
You have taken everything
that has meant anything to me!

21:54.741 --> 21:55.607
You have--

21:55.659 --> 21:56.775
[ Thud ]

22:01.415 --> 22:03.365
Betty: [ Scoffs ]

22:03.417 --> 22:04.749
Get a blanket.

22:04.785 --> 22:06.434
Austin: [ Snoring ]

22:21.018 --> 22:22.517
[ Door opens ]

22:25.138 --> 22:26.438
William: Dennis.

22:26.473 --> 22:29.257
What are you--
what are you doing?

22:32.095 --> 22:34.763
Dennis:
You're a doctor, right?

22:34.798 --> 22:37.999
I mean, you help people?

22:38.035 --> 22:41.736
William: I-I do.

22:43.957 --> 22:49.244
Dennis: I, um, heard
you wrote a book about...

22:51.715 --> 22:54.516
people's private parts.

22:54.551 --> 22:57.335
William: About sex-- yes.
Yes, I did.

22:59.756 --> 23:01.506
Is everything all right?

23:05.929 --> 23:08.229
Dennis: I don't think so.

23:08.265 --> 23:09.314
I think...

23:12.102 --> 23:15.070
something's wrong with me.

23:15.105 --> 23:17.656
William: And originally,
it gets produced in here.

23:17.691 --> 23:20.175
It's called
a nocturnal emission

23:20.210 --> 23:23.044
or, colloquially,
a wet dream.

23:23.080 --> 23:27.015
It's incredibly common
and perfectly normal.

23:27.050 --> 23:29.084
Dennis: Are you sure?

23:29.119 --> 23:30.885
William:
I couldn't be more sure.

23:30.921 --> 23:33.955
Hasn't your father or...

23:34.007 --> 23:37.025
someone explained
any of this to you?

23:41.548 --> 23:43.014
Dennis: - Ow!
William: - John!

23:43.050 --> 23:44.632
Johnny:
Get out of my house!

23:44.685 --> 23:46.034
This is my house!

23:46.069 --> 23:47.435
Get out!

23:50.907 --> 23:53.108
[ Door opens ]

23:56.713 --> 23:57.746
[ Knocks on door ]

24:01.852 --> 24:03.952
Betty:
Austin, what are you doing?

24:03.987 --> 24:07.522
Austin: I can't sleep.

24:07.557 --> 24:10.325
Can I sleep with you?

24:10.360 --> 24:12.260
Betty: When hell freezes over.

24:12.295 --> 24:13.328
Austin: But I'm miserable.

24:13.363 --> 24:15.096
I also threw up.

24:15.132 --> 24:19.134
Betty: - Where?
Austin: - In the john.

24:19.169 --> 24:20.802
But I still feel awful.

24:20.837 --> 24:24.172
Betty: Okay.

24:24.174 --> 24:27.642
I'll get you some ginger ale.
It'll settle your stomach.

24:30.013 --> 24:32.430
Austin:
I don't know how I got here.

24:32.482 --> 24:37.018
I mean, how did I become,

24:37.020 --> 24:39.854
God, such a giant fuck-up.

24:39.856 --> 24:43.324
Betty: Hey. You were a...
pretty good doctor

24:43.360 --> 24:46.111
and a really good
diet-pill salesman.

24:46.163 --> 24:48.580
Austin:
That was all bullshit--

24:48.665 --> 24:50.365
the opposite of
when I'm with my kids.

24:50.367 --> 24:53.118
That's when
I was really myself--

24:53.170 --> 24:55.370
watching "Lost In Space,"

24:55.422 --> 24:58.540
playing concentration,

24:58.592 --> 24:59.841
grilled cheese.

24:59.876 --> 25:02.844
Betty: Well, you are...
on their level.

25:02.879 --> 25:04.579
That is for sure.

25:04.614 --> 25:06.681
Austin: I always figured having
kids would force me to grow up,

25:06.716 --> 25:09.684
but... it was the total opposite.

25:12.722 --> 25:17.192
I knew who I was with my kids.

25:17.227 --> 25:18.693
It's the only thing
I was good at.

25:18.728 --> 25:21.329
Betty: That is not true.

25:21.364 --> 25:23.114
Austin:
You know it's true, Betty.

25:23.150 --> 25:25.066
I know it's true.
That's the problem.

25:27.120 --> 25:28.236
Can I have some more?

25:33.460 --> 25:36.461
♪

25:39.916 --> 25:41.299
Virginia: You are here today

25:41.334 --> 25:46.421
because science is on the cusp
of a startling discovery--

25:46.456 --> 25:48.139
a discovery about
how and why

25:48.175 --> 25:51.059
we are attracted
to one another.

25:51.094 --> 25:54.395
It appears that human beings
emit certain chemicals.

25:54.431 --> 25:57.765
Now, these chemicals--
pheromones, they're called--

25:57.818 --> 26:00.185
work to attract us
to one another.

26:01.822 --> 26:03.238
Pheromones don't smell,

26:03.273 --> 26:05.940
and yet we believe that they're
detected through the nose,

26:05.942 --> 26:07.775
sensed, if you will.

26:07.828 --> 26:11.613
And these pheromones travel
from one person to the next,

26:11.665 --> 26:14.115
sending secret messages
of sorts,

26:14.167 --> 26:18.453
directly into our brains
to grab our sexual attention--

26:18.505 --> 26:20.955
a raw sexual attractant,

26:21.041 --> 26:23.591
pure animal magnetism.

26:29.432 --> 26:32.767
Virginia:
[ Breathing heavily ]

26:40.810 --> 26:42.810
[ Breathing heavily ]

26:51.087 --> 26:53.955
[ Moaning ]

26:53.990 --> 26:56.991
♪

27:25.522 --> 27:27.605
Betty:
Uh, I need some invoices signed,

27:27.657 --> 27:28.990
but the doc isn't in yet.

27:37.117 --> 27:39.450
So, how you doing?

27:39.502 --> 27:40.868
Virginia: Fine.

27:42.372 --> 27:43.905
Betty:
How's Dan Logan doing?

27:47.127 --> 27:49.177
Virginia: Fine. I think.

27:49.212 --> 27:53.464
Betty: Can I say something,

27:53.516 --> 27:57.802
uh, you know, honestly,
but also in confidence?

27:57.854 --> 27:58.886
Virginia: Of course.

28:02.892 --> 28:04.359
Betty: I think the doc

28:04.394 --> 28:10.064
is a little worried
about Mr. Logan,

28:10.066 --> 28:16.287
about the, uh--
the effect that he's--

28:16.323 --> 28:18.740
well, he's having on you.

28:18.742 --> 28:19.824
Virginia: I'm sorry.

28:19.876 --> 28:21.576
- Uh, the effect?
Betty: - But, actually,

28:21.628 --> 28:24.245
I'm a little bit more worried
about the doc, to be honest.

28:24.281 --> 28:29.484
I-I think he's a little...
undone by Mr. Logan's presence.

28:29.519 --> 28:32.754
Virginia:
So, Bill sent you to...

28:32.789 --> 28:34.188
pump me for information?

28:36.159 --> 28:37.892
Betty:
He asked me to inquire.

28:37.927 --> 28:41.095
But the only reason
I'm even doing that

28:41.147 --> 28:43.731
is 'cause...
I came a long way

28:43.767 --> 28:45.650
to get to that desk chair
out there,

28:45.685 --> 28:46.818
and I have no interest

28:46.853 --> 28:48.670
in watching
this whole operation blow.

28:48.705 --> 28:50.772
Virginia:
Nothing is going to blow.

28:50.824 --> 28:53.441
[ Chuckles ]
Betty.

28:53.443 --> 28:56.611
Tell Bill that--
that we spoke

28:56.613 --> 29:01.199
and that I reassured you
that everything is fine.

29:01.251 --> 29:03.584
Mr. Logan and I
are simply moving on

29:03.620 --> 29:06.220
to the next stage
of the scent research.

29:07.524 --> 29:09.724
Which is true, Betty.

29:11.294 --> 29:12.927
[ Telephone rings ]

29:20.437 --> 29:22.637
Betty: Reproductive Biology
Research Foundation.

29:22.639 --> 29:25.189
[ Elevator dings ]

29:25.225 --> 29:28.209
[ Indistinct conversations ]

29:42.325 --> 29:44.392
Betty: Did you, uh,
check on top of the fridge?

29:44.427 --> 29:45.827
Austin: I already looked there.

29:45.829 --> 29:48.079
Betty: Well, then maybe Helen
finished the frosted flakes.

29:48.131 --> 29:50.331
Austin: But that's what I eat
for breakfast every day.

29:50.383 --> 29:51.883
Betty:
Well, then fry an egg, then.

29:51.918 --> 29:54.001
Just don't leave the
refrigerator door hanging open.

29:54.054 --> 29:55.219
Oh, I got to go.

29:55.255 --> 29:57.572
William: Are you--
are you hiding from me?

29:57.607 --> 29:58.389
Betty: Hiding?

29:58.425 --> 29:59.807
No. That would just be silly.

29:59.843 --> 30:01.576
William: Because I-I just saw
you talking with Virginia.

30:01.611 --> 30:03.044
Betty: I'm hiding from you

30:03.079 --> 30:05.747
because I do not want to have
this conversation.

30:05.782 --> 30:07.515
William:
Why? What did Virginia say?

30:07.517 --> 30:08.683
Betty: First of all,

30:08.735 --> 30:10.768
there is nothing going on
between her and Logan.

30:10.820 --> 30:11.819
William: She said that?

30:11.855 --> 30:13.354
Well, of course
she said that now.

30:13.406 --> 30:15.773
But what if you were to take her
out for dinner, you know?

30:15.859 --> 30:17.525
- Maybe have a drink or two?
Betty: - No!

30:17.577 --> 30:20.244
My responsibilities here
are varied and far-reaching,

30:20.280 --> 30:22.447
but reffing a fight
between mommy and daddy

30:22.499 --> 30:23.531
is not one of them.

30:23.583 --> 30:27.034
William: - [ Sighs ]
Betty: - Hey, hey.

30:27.087 --> 30:29.370
Maybe I can spare you
a lot of grief

30:29.372 --> 30:32.173
by sharing with you a tidbit
I've picked up--

30:32.208 --> 30:33.875
one you seem to have missed.

30:33.877 --> 30:39.213
Trying to control other people
doesn't work, ever.

30:39.265 --> 30:43.684
The only person you can control
is yourself.

30:45.305 --> 30:47.138
William: So, you got no relevant
information out of her

30:47.190 --> 30:49.524
- about Logan.
Betty: - Oh, for the love of God!

30:49.559 --> 30:51.392
Are you kidding me?

30:51.444 --> 30:55.029
William: The placebo reaction.
With scents?

30:55.064 --> 30:57.064
Virginia: The preliminary
results are very interesting.

30:57.066 --> 30:58.483
Would you like to see them?

30:58.535 --> 31:00.118
William: So, Logan didn't get
the, uh, results he wanted,

31:00.153 --> 31:01.636
and now he wants to test
fake results.

31:01.671 --> 31:03.337
Virginia: No.

31:03.373 --> 31:05.706
No, I wanted to study
the power of suggestion,

31:05.742 --> 31:08.626
something that you and I have
talked about in our own work.

31:08.661 --> 31:09.710
William: Virginia, it--

31:11.631 --> 31:15.666
is there any, uh...
particular reason

31:15.718 --> 31:19.153
you're insisting
he stay here?

31:23.009 --> 31:25.893
Virginia: I'm making lemonade
out of lemons, Bill.

31:25.929 --> 31:27.311
I didn't want Dan Logan

31:27.347 --> 31:29.597
to join us
as our principle investor,

31:29.682 --> 31:30.765
if you'll recall.

31:30.767 --> 31:32.233
I wanted Hugh Hefner.

31:32.268 --> 31:35.603
But you ignored my request,
not for the first time,

31:35.655 --> 31:37.155
and as a result,

31:37.190 --> 31:39.106
I have found something
in his work

31:39.159 --> 31:41.526
that adds value to our work,

31:41.578 --> 31:43.077
an avenue that invites study.

31:43.112 --> 31:44.111
William:
If you want to investigate

31:44.164 --> 31:45.913
the psychosomatic effects
of treatment,

31:45.949 --> 31:48.249
in five seconds,
I could design a study

31:48.284 --> 31:50.501
that is far more tailored
to our work

31:50.537 --> 31:54.622
than some-- some phony
sniff test with Logan.

31:54.674 --> 31:57.208
Virginia: Even if he does go,

31:57.260 --> 32:00.261
you can't force me to work on
your surrogacy program.

32:00.296 --> 32:03.264
William: -<i> My</i> surrogacy program?
Virginia: - Isn't it your program

32:03.299 --> 32:06.100
if you're going forward with it
regardless of my objections?

32:06.135 --> 32:07.802
Bill, I haven't put my foot down

32:07.854 --> 32:10.304
about something
that <i> you</i> are interested in,

32:10.340 --> 32:13.274
and so I would expect
the same consideration from you.

32:13.309 --> 32:15.860
In fact, I insist upon it.

32:15.895 --> 32:20.064
The institute
that bears both our names

32:20.116 --> 32:23.568
has enough room
to accommodate us both.

